  "body": "## Preamable\r\n```\r\nVIP: 1000\r\nTitle: Only bools should be used as logical values.\r\nAuthor: Ryuya Nakamura (@nrryuya)\r\nType: Standard Track\r\nStatus: Draft\r\nCreated: 18-8-2018\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Simple Summary\r\nOnly bools should be used as a logical value for simplicity and security.\r\n\r\n## Abstract\r\nNow values whose type is not `bool` can used in `assert` and `if`.\r\n(The code below can be compiled in [vyper.online](https://vyper.online/))\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22876645/44295095-f9aa6a00-a2dc-11e8-9672-0e051da75002.png)\r\n\r\n\r\nHowever, only `bool` values should be used as a logical value.\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nIn Python, syntaxes like `if some_object:` are used to check the existence of `some_object`. However, in Vyper we can code like `if n != 0:` (e.g. n is `int128`) because every types has default value other than `None`. I think the latter is easier to understand and better for auditability.\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nCompiler allow only bools to be used as a logical value.\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nThe codes in which values whose type is not `bool` is used as logical value will not be compiled anymore.\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
